\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}4a=4c$
\end_inset

 which is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since both cases are true, given 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $4\mid\left(x^{4}-x^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\equiv c\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv c\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

.
 If we know 
\begin_inset Formula $11\equiv-3\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-3\equiv4\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

, can we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $11\equiv4\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid\left(a-b\right)$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to saying that 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b=ng$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a-ng$
\end_inset

.
 We can use this identity in the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $b\equiv c\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

 by writing the equivalent form 
\begin_inset Formula $b-c=nl$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $l\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, and substituting in 
\begin_inset Formula $a-ng$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b-c & =nl\\
a-ng-c & =nl\\
a-c & =nl+ng\\
a-c & =n\left(l+g\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a-c$
\end_inset

 or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv c\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

.
 And of course this proof shows that the answer to the question is yes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This is a biconditional, so we will prove both direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\implies\right):$
\end_inset

 We begin by showing directly that if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to saying 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3c$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this in for 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{2}=3\left(3c^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\impliedby\right):$
\end_inset

 Next we show directly by cases that if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 An integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 can be written as either 
\begin_inset Formula $3k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $3k+1$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $3k+2$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Only in the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we need to show that in the other two cases, that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

 is false.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Case
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k$
\end_inset

, substituting this into the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid3\left(3k^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Which is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k+1$
\end_inset

, substituting this into the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(3\left(3k^{2}+2k\right)+1\right)$
\end_inset

 which is false since 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k+2$
\end_inset

, substituting this into the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $3|n^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(3\left(3k^{2}+4k\right)+2\right)$
\end_inset

 which is false since 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 does not divide 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

, which completes the proof.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Prove 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(2n^{2}+1\right)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\nmid n$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This is a biconditional, so we will prove both direction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\implies\right):$
\end_inset

 We suppose contrapositively that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3a$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into 
\begin_inset Formula $2n^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
2n^{2}+1 & =18a^{2}+1\\
 & =3\left(6a^{2}\right)+1,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which does not divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 does not divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(2n^{2}+1\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $3\nmid n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\impliedby\right):$
\end_inset

 We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $3\nmid n$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 can be written as either 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k+1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $3k+2$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If the statement holds for both cases, then it is true.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Case
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k+1$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into 
\begin_inset Formula $2n^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
2n^{2}+1 & =2\left(9k^{2}+6k+1\right)+1\\
 & =18k^{2}+12k+3\\
 & =3\left(6k^{2}+4k+1\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which does divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3k+2$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $2n^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
2n^{2}+1 & =2\left(9k^{2}+12k+4\right)+1\\
 & =18k^{2}+24k+9\\
 & =3\left(6k^{2}+8k+3\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which does divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since both cases hold, if 
\begin_inset Formula $3\nmid n$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3\mid\left(2n^{2}+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d,n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\equiv d\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

, prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $ac\equiv bd\,\mod\:n$
\end_inset

.
 What does this statement say if we take 
\begin_inset Formula $c=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=b$
\end_inset

? We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $19\equiv5\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

.
 Do we then know 
\begin_inset Formula $19^{2}\equiv5^{2}\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

.
 How about 
\begin_inset Formula $19^{3}\equiv5^{3}\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

?.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\equiv d\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

, which is equivalent to supposing 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b=ng$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c-d=nk$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k,g\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $a=ng+b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=nk+d$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ac=ngnk-dng-bnk+bd,
\]

\end_inset

which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
ad-bd & =ngnk-dng-bnk\\
 & =n\left(ngk-dg-bk\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid ad-bd$
\end_inset

, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $ac\equiv bd\,\mod\:n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under the conditions that 
\begin_inset Formula $c=a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=b$
\end_inset

, the statement that we proves says that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}\equiv b^{2}\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

.
 This means that if 
\begin_inset Formula $19\equiv5\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $19^{2}\equiv5^{2}\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

.
 To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $19^{3}\equiv5^{3}\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b=ng$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a^{3} & =n^{3}g^{3}+n^{2}g^{2}b+2n^{2}g^{2}b+2ngb^{2}+ngb^{2}+b^{3}\\
 & =n\left(n^{2}g^{3}+3ng^{2}b+3gb^{2}\right)+b^{3},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{3}-b^{3}=n\left(n^{2}g^{3}+3ng^{2}b+3gb^{2}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This shows that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{3}\equiv b^{3}\,\mod\,n$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $19^{3}\equiv5^{3}\,\mod\,7$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

