\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\not\in\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a rational number it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathbb{Z}-\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y$
\end_inset

 is rational, it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{c}{d}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Z}-\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{c}{d}$
\end_inset

 which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{cb-ad}{bd}$
\end_inset

 which must be rational and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $y\not\in\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove: If we are given a nonzero rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and an irrational number 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, then the number 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 is irrational.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We assume by contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Q}-\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}-\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

, and the rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{c}{d}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Z}-\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y & =xy/x\\
 & =\frac{c}{d}\frac{b}{a}\\
 & =\frac{cb}{da},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is rational.
 This is contradictory since 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 was stated to be irrational.
 Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Prove there is no smallest positive irrational number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose by contradiction that there is a smallest positive irrational
 number 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We know from the previous proof that given a nonzero rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and an irrational number 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, then the number 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 is irrational.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset

 must be irrational.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{b}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\left\{ x\in\mathbb{Z},x>1\right\} $
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xz>0$
\end_inset

, is still positive and an irrational number.
 In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $xz=\frac{z}{b}$
\end_inset

 which must be smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This is contradictory to our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 was the smallest positive irrational number.
 Thus there is not smallest positive irrational number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $33x+132y\neq57$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose by contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $33x+132y=57$
\end_inset

 which can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $33\left(x+4y\right)=57$
\end_inset

 or equivalently as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x+4y=\frac{19}{11}.
\]

\end_inset

Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{19}{11}-4y$
\end_inset

 which is not an integer since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{19}{11}$
\end_inset

 is not an integer.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $33x+132y\neq57$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are integers.
\end_layout

